Héma-Québec yesterday celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its chairman, Dre Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the suppliers of the security and more efficient in the world. 
Above all, it has regained the confidence of the public who had been seriously damaged by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s. 
As we know, the national reserves of blood transfusion service run by the Canadian Red Cross have been infected by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s. 
Faced with this tragedy and the public, the government of Canada has established in February 1994 a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which was intended to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster never happens again. 
While the judge Krever delayed to submit his report, some provinces have set up a committee to plan a new system of management of the blood in Canada. 
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has fulfilled the mandate. 
Following the reports Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve the Quebec and the Canadian Society of blood to supply all the other provinces and two territories. 
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, only 38% of people still had confidence in the system of blood in Quebec, recalls the Dre Décary. 
The situation was discouraging. 
In force of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground during the years that followed, we have regained the confidence of the public, "she said before proudly say that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population has confidence in Héma-Québec. 
The Décary guard Dre, however, that "confidence is something extremely fragile.". 
Since its creation, the 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle. 
At that time, we have seen in Europe to many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is the strong since its foundation in 1998. 
"And we did not know whether the disease could be transmitted by blood. 
We then relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports that when we do not know, and that can lead to serious disease, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, introduction of measures. 
In April 1999, it has refused the blood of the people who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980. 
However, there are a few years, it has been proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood. 
The episode has shown that the precautionary principle that has been applied had sense. " 
In 1999 appeared on the market a much more sensitive technical HIV screening tests: the nucleic acid (TAN), which can detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, which stood the tests used so far. 
The TAN have helped to shorten the period silent, which stretches between the time when the person has been infected and that when the first virus can be detected in the blood of our technical expert, said. 
It has been able to reduce this period to less than a week. 
It has dwindled substantially the risk that some donors are infected without knowing it and that we can detect. 
These improvements have helped to reduce the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion. 
Today, one in 12 million runs the risk of blood contaminated with HIV. 
"In other words, it means that it will distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV. 
As Héma-Québec distributes each year between 400 and 500 000 000 blood products, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by blood products. 
I believe that we can now feel comfortable to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover the health, "said the head of the direction of Héma-Québec. 
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products. 
You never know what virus will emerge in the system. 
Just last year appeared on the island of Réunion the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood. 
We must be constantly vigilant, "said the Décary Dre before stress that security of supply, Héma-Québec must also include an adequate supply. 
"The needs are increasing because the population is ageing. 
The anti-cancer treatments being more aggressive, patients often need a refill in red blood cells or platelets. 
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors which includes on average only 3% of Québécois eligible for blood. " 
Any person in health, aged 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can give blood all 56 days, six times a year. 
On average, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted, because they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travelled in a country where there is malaria, they will be excluded for a period of one year. 
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory which responds to the needs of the hospitals. 
The shortages are very rare. 
But we must renew the members of this network of donors as they mature and can no longer give blood. 
However, it is difficult to convince people to give blood, but above all to remember and to encourage them to become regular donors. 
The life of today is so fast, there is rarely the time to spend an hour to give blood, "Francine Décary. 
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also of human tissue, including bone graft, cardiac valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for burns. 
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored in Héma-Québec, which is also the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec. 
The umbilical cord which was once seen as a biomedical waste is full of a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukaemia. 
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the bank of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and we take more than a thousand per year. 
We should begin to propose for transplants at the beginning of next year, "said the Dre Décary which describes this programme to levy umbilical cord blood as very popular. 
